1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,689
Welcome back to the Articulate Journal.

2
00:00:02,689 --> 00:00:06,974
In the previous episode, I introduced
Articulate: a product intended

3
00:00:06,974 --> 00:00:11,260
to help architects discover, understand,
design and evolve complex systems

4
00:00:11,260 --> 00:00:13,150
through collaboration with AI.

5
00:00:13,150 --> 00:00:16,238
I also introduced the journal surrounding
it.

6
00:00:16,238 --> 00:00:20,524
The journal makes the architectural
thinking visible: the problems being

7
00:00:20,524 --> 00:00:24,809
explored, the principles guiding the
design, the decisions being made,

8
00:00:24,809 --> 00:00:27,897
and the implementation that emerges from
them.

9
00:00:27,897 --> 00:00:32,183
But Articulate itself is not intended to
be a temporary

10
00:00:32,183 --> 00:00:33,674
proof of concept.

11
00:00:33,674 --> 00:00:37,161
The aim is to build a real product.

12
00:00:37,161 --> 00:00:41,447
The architecture will evolve, and some
decisions will change, but

13
00:00:41,447 --> 00:00:45,732
the software is being built with long-term
use, maintainability and

14
00:00:45,732 --> 00:00:47,224
evolution in mind.

15
00:00:47,224 --> 00:00:49,513
That creates an important question.

16
00:00:49,513 --> 00:00:53,799
Why should a product like Articulate be
designed as an

17
00:00:53,799 --> 00:00:58,084
AI-native system rather than as a
conventional application with AI

18
00:00:58,084 --> 00:00:59,975
features added to it?

19
00:00:59,975 --> 00:01:04,261
Before exploring the architecture in more
detail, I want to

20
00:01:04,261 --> 00:01:08,546
explain what I currently mean by
AI-native, how it differs

21
00:01:08,546 --> 00:01:12,832
from AI-powered, and why that distinction
shapes the system I

22
00:01:12,832 --> 00:01:14,209
am building.

23
00:01:14,209 --> 00:01:18,494
Because AI-native is one of those terms
that is being

24
00:01:18,494 --> 00:01:22,780
used more and more, but it doesn't
necessarily mean the

25
00:01:22,780 --> 00:01:24,670
same thing to everyone.

26
00:01:24,670 --> 00:01:28,956
Terms like AI-native, agentic systems, AI
agents, multi-agent system, and

27
00:01:28,956 --> 00:01:31,645
even reasoning models are still evolving.

28
00:01:31,645 --> 00:01:35,930
Different organisations, vendors and
researchers use them in slightly different

29
00:01:35,930 --> 00:01:40,216
ways, and I fully expect the language to
continue changing

30
00:01:40,216 --> 00:01:42,106
as the technology matures.

31
00:01:42,106 --> 00:01:46,392
So what I'm describing here isn't intended
to be the

32
00:01:46,392 --> 00:01:48,681
definitive definition of AI-native
architecture.

33
00:01:48,681 --> 00:01:52,967
It's my current understanding with the
research I've been doing.

34
00:01:52,967 --> 00:01:56,454
And that distinction is important for this
journal.

35
00:01:56,454 --> 00:02:00,740
Some of the ideas I describe today will
almost certainly

36
00:02:00,740 --> 00:02:02,231
be refined later.

37
00:02:02,231 --> 00:02:04,121
Some might be challenged.

38
00:02:04,121 --> 00:02:06,810
Some may eventually be replaced
completely.

39
00:02:06,810 --> 00:02:09,898
I don't see that as a problem.

40
00:02:09,898 --> 00:02:14,184
I see it as part of the process of
learning

41
00:02:14,184 --> 00:02:18,469
how to architect systems around a
technology that is itself

42
00:02:18,469 --> 00:02:19,846
still evolving.

43
00:02:19,846 --> 00:02:24,132
So, with that context, what do I actually
mean by

44
00:02:24,132 --> 00:02:25,623
an AI-native system?

45
00:02:25,623 --> 00:02:29,909
Over the last few years, lots of software
products seems

46
00:02:29,909 --> 00:02:31,799
to have become AI-powered.

47
00:02:31,799 --> 00:02:36,085
And in many cases, what that really means
is that

48
00:02:36,085 --> 00:02:40,370
an existing application has had an LLM
added to it.

49
00:02:40,370 --> 00:02:42,660
Perhaps there's now a chatbot.

50
00:02:42,660 --> 00:02:45,349
Perhaps a feature generates some text.

51
00:02:45,349 --> 00:02:49,634
Or perhaps the application sends a prompt
to a model,

52
00:02:49,634 --> 00:02:52,722
receives a response, and displays the
result.

53
00:02:52,722 --> 00:02:55,411
There's nothing inherently wrong with
that.

54
00:02:55,411 --> 00:02:59,697
But architecturally, the application is
still fundamentally the same system.

55
00:02:59,697 --> 00:03:03,982
If you removed the AI capability, most of
the architecture

56
00:03:03,982 --> 00:03:05,473
would remain intact.

57
00:03:05,473 --> 00:03:08,961
That isn't the approach I'm taking with
Articulate.

58
00:03:08,961 --> 00:03:13,246
Articulate is being designed as an
AI-native system (AI first).

59
00:03:13,246 --> 00:03:15,536
The distinction is relatively simple.

60
00:03:15,536 --> 00:03:17,825
An AI-powered system uses AI.

61
00:03:17,825 --> 00:03:20,913
An AI-native system is built around it.

62
00:03:20,913 --> 00:03:25,199
In an AI-native system, intelligence
participates in the runtime itself.

63
00:03:25,199 --> 00:03:29,884
It isn't simply waiting for somebody to
send it a prompt.

64
00:03:29,884 --> 00:03:32,972
It might be helping to understand intent.

65
00:03:32,972 --> 00:03:34,862
Building and maintaining context.

66
00:03:34,862 --> 00:03:36,353
Retrieving relevant knowledge.

67
00:03:36,353 --> 00:03:38,244
Reasoning about a problem.

68
00:03:38,244 --> 00:03:40,534
Deciding what should happen next.

69
00:03:40,534 --> 00:03:41,911
Invoking tools.

70
00:03:41,911 --> 00:03:43,288
Coordinating work.

71
00:03:43,288 --> 00:03:46,775
Evaluating the confidence it has in a
result.

72
00:03:46,775 --> 00:03:51,061
And, importantly, knowing when a human
needs to be involved.

73
00:03:51,061 --> 00:03:54,149
That changes the architecture of the
system.

74
00:03:54,149 --> 00:03:58,434
Traditional applications are often
designed around things like CRUD
operations,

75
00:03:58,434 --> 00:04:00,724
APIs, transactions and deterministic
workflows.

76
00:04:00,724 --> 00:04:02,614
We know the inputs.

77
00:04:02,614 --> 00:04:04,505
We define the process.

78
00:04:04,505 --> 00:04:07,593
And, generally, we expect a predictable
output.

79
00:04:07,593 --> 00:04:11,479
AI-native systems introduce a different
set of architectural concerns.

80
00:04:11,479 --> 00:04:14,567
Now we have to think about context.

81
00:04:14,567 --> 00:04:15,944
Memory.

82
00:04:15,944 --> 00:04:17,321
Knowledge.

83
00:04:17,321 --> 00:04:18,699
Reasoning.

84
00:04:18,699 --> 00:04:20,076
Orchestration.

85
00:04:20,076 --> 00:04:21,453
Conversation.

86
00:04:21,453 --> 00:04:22,830
And uncertainty.

87
00:04:22,830 --> 00:04:25,918
That doesn't mean the traditional concerns
disappear.

88
00:04:25,918 --> 00:04:28,607
We still need APIs and databases.

89
00:04:28,607 --> 00:04:32,892
We still need transactions, messaging,
security, observability and all of

90
00:04:32,892 --> 00:04:36,380
the other things that make production
systems work.

91
00:04:36,380 --> 00:04:40,266
But intelligence becomes another
fundamental part of the runtime.

92
00:04:40,266 --> 00:04:44,551
And I think that's one of the most
important architectural

93
00:04:44,551 --> 00:04:46,043
shifts taking place.

94
00:04:46,043 --> 00:04:50,727
As systems became distributed, we added
messaging, networking and distributed
coordination.

95
00:04:50,727 --> 00:04:54,215
Cloud computing introduced another
generation of runtime capabilities.

96
00:04:54,215 --> 00:04:56,504
AI-native systems introduce something
else.

97
00:04:56,504 --> 00:04:59,193
Intelligence itself starts to become
infrastructure.

98
00:04:59,193 --> 00:05:03,479
Instead of every part of the application
making isolated calls

99
00:05:03,479 --> 00:05:07,764
to an LLM, the system begins to need
shared capabilities

100
00:05:07,764 --> 00:05:12,050
for reasoning, memory, semantic retrieval,
tool invocation, evaluation and
orchestration.

101
00:05:12,050 --> 00:05:16,335
And once those capabilities become part of
the runtime, we

102
00:05:16,335 --> 00:05:18,625
have to architect them deliberately.

103
00:05:18,625 --> 00:05:22,112
We have to think about how they're
governed.

104
00:05:22,112 --> 00:05:24,801
How they're observed, how they fail.

105
00:05:24,801 --> 00:05:28,687
How state is maintained and how decisions
are explained.

106
00:05:28,687 --> 00:05:32,973
And how humans remain involved when the
system cannot, or

107
00:05:32,973 --> 00:05:34,863
should not, act independently.

108
00:05:34,863 --> 00:05:38,750
This is also where agentic systems enter
the conversation.

109
00:05:38,750 --> 00:05:43,035
The terms AI-native and agentic are
sometimes used almost interchangeably,

110
00:05:43,035 --> 00:05:46,522
but I don't think they're the same thing.

111
00:05:46,522 --> 00:05:49,610
I see AI-native as an architectural
philosophy.

112
00:05:49,610 --> 00:05:54,694
Agentic systems are one possible pattern
for organising intelligence within that
architecture.

113
00:05:54,694 --> 00:05:57,383
An agent might have a goal.

114
00:05:57,383 --> 00:06:00,870
It might plan how to achieve that goal.

115
00:06:00,870 --> 00:06:05,156
It might retrieve information, use tools,
delegate work, collaborate with

116
00:06:05,156 --> 00:06:09,441
other agents, reflect on its own results,
and maintain some

117
00:06:09,441 --> 00:06:10,933
form of memory.

118
00:06:10,933 --> 00:06:12,823
Those are useful capabilities.

119
00:06:12,823 --> 00:06:17,109
But adding an agent to an existing
application doesn't automatically

120
00:06:17,109 --> 00:06:18,999
make that application AI-native.

121
00:06:18,999 --> 00:06:23,285
And an AI-native system doesn't
necessarily need to consist of

122
00:06:23,285 --> 00:06:26,772
dozens of autonomous agents talking to
each other.

123
00:06:26,772 --> 00:06:31,456
That's something I want to be careful
about as Articulate evolves.

124
00:06:31,456 --> 00:06:36,540
The goal isn't to add agents everywhere
simply because agents are interesting.

125
00:06:36,540 --> 00:06:40,826
The architecture should use agentic
behaviour where that behaviour genuinely

126
00:06:40,826 --> 00:06:42,716
helps solve the problem.

127
00:06:42,716 --> 00:06:47,002
Agents are one architectural pattern
available to an AI-native system.

128
00:06:47,002 --> 00:06:49,691
They aren't the definition of one.

129
00:06:49,691 --> 00:06:53,178
So why does Articulate need to be
AI-native?

130
00:06:53,178 --> 00:06:57,463
Because the problem I'm trying to explore
isn't simply how

131
00:06:57,463 --> 00:07:00,551
to generate architecture documents using
an LLM.

132
00:07:00,551 --> 00:07:04,039
AI needs to participate throughout the
architectural process.

133
00:07:04,039 --> 00:07:06,727
Articulate needs to understand
architectural intent.

134
00:07:06,727 --> 00:07:09,416
It needs to conduct guided discovery.

135
00:07:09,416 --> 00:07:13,702
It needs to ask useful questions and
identify where important

136
00:07:13,702 --> 00:07:15,193
information is missing.

137
00:07:15,193 --> 00:07:18,680
It needs to build contextual understanding
over time.

138
00:07:18,680 --> 00:07:22,567
It needs to retrieve and reason over
architectural knowledge.

139
00:07:22,567 --> 00:07:27,251
It needs to help produce capability models
and other architectural artefacts.

140
00:07:27,251 --> 00:07:30,339
It needs to evaluate confidence and
uncertainty.

141
00:07:30,339 --> 00:07:34,625
And ultimately, it needs to collaborate
with a human architect

142
00:07:34,625 --> 00:07:38,112
throughout the process of understanding
and designing systems.

143
00:07:38,112 --> 00:07:43,196
If I removed AI from Articulate, I
wouldn't simply lose a feature.

144
00:07:43,196 --> 00:07:46,683
I would have to fundamentally redesign the
system.

145
00:07:46,683 --> 00:07:50,969
And for me, that's probably the clearest
test of whether

146
00:07:50,969 --> 00:07:52,859
something is genuinely AI-native.

147
00:07:52,859 --> 00:07:57,145
Another important consequence of this is
the role of conversation.

148
00:07:57,145 --> 00:08:01,430
One of the ideas throughout Articulate is
that AI-native systems

149
00:08:01,430 --> 00:08:03,321
can become conversation-driven systems.

150
00:08:03,321 --> 00:08:07,606
And I don't mean simply putting a chat
window on

151
00:08:07,606 --> 00:08:09,497
top of an application.

152
00:08:09,497 --> 00:08:12,984
Conversation can become part of the
runtime itself.

153
00:08:12,984 --> 00:08:18,068
It's how a human expresses intent, how
thesystem asks for missing information.

154
00:08:18,068 --> 00:08:22,752
It's how context develops over time and
how knowledge is discovered.

155
00:08:22,752 --> 00:08:25,441
It's how decisions can be explored.

156
00:08:25,441 --> 00:08:30,126
And it's how workflows can be initiated,
paused, redirected and continued.

157
00:08:30,126 --> 00:08:34,012
In Articulate, architectural artefacts
should emerge from that collaboration.

158
00:08:34,012 --> 00:08:37,100
The conversation isn't separate from the
work.

159
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:40,987
The conversation is part of how the work
happens.

160
00:08:40,987 --> 00:08:45,272
That leads to a set of principles that I
expect

161
00:08:45,272 --> 00:08:47,961
to return to throughout this journal.

162
00:08:47,961 --> 00:08:51,448
Intelligence should be treated as a
runtime capability.

163
00:08:51,448 --> 00:08:54,935
Conversation should be treated as a
primary interface.

164
00:08:54,935 --> 00:08:57,624
Context becomes a form of state.

165
00:08:57,624 --> 00:09:01,111
Memory needs to extend beyond a single
request.

166
00:09:01,111 --> 00:09:06,195
Knowledge should be retrieved and evolved
rather than simply embedded into prompts.

167
00:09:06,195 --> 00:09:09,682
Humans remain an essential part of the
system.

168
00:09:09,682 --> 00:09:13,169
Uncertainty has to be represented rather
than hidden.

169
00:09:13,169 --> 00:09:16,657
And evaluation is just as important as
execution.

170
00:09:16,657 --> 00:09:18,946
These aren't implementation decisions yet.

171
00:09:18,946 --> 00:09:20,438
They're architectural principles.

172
00:09:20,438 --> 00:09:22,328
And that distinction matters.

173
00:09:22,328 --> 00:09:26,614
I haven't decided that Articulate needs a
particular agent framework,

174
00:09:26,614 --> 00:09:29,702
workflow engine, vector database or model
provider.

175
00:09:29,702 --> 00:09:31,991
Those decisions should come later.

176
00:09:31,991 --> 00:09:35,079
First, I want to understand the problem.

177
00:09:35,079 --> 00:09:36,970
Then establish the principles.

178
00:09:36,970 --> 00:09:40,457
Then identify the capabilities the system
actually needs.

179
00:09:40,457 --> 00:09:45,142
And only then start making decisions about
architecture, runtime and technology.

180
00:09:45,142 --> 00:09:48,230
That is really what this episode
establishes.

181
00:09:48,230 --> 00:09:52,515
If intelligence becomes a first-class part
of a system, then

182
00:09:52,515 --> 00:09:56,801
we need to think differently about the
runtime that supports

183
00:09:56,801 --> 00:09:58,178
it.

184
00:09:58,178 --> 00:10:00,468
What does context actually mean?

185
00:10:00,468 --> 00:10:04,354
What forms of memory does an AI-native
system need?

186
00:10:04,354 --> 00:10:07,043
How should architectural knowledge be
represented?

187
00:10:07,043 --> 00:10:10,929
How should AI retrieve and reason over
that knowledge?

188
00:10:10,929 --> 00:10:13,219
Where should we use agents?

189
00:10:13,219 --> 00:10:15,908
How do we coordinate long-running work?

190
00:10:15,908 --> 00:10:18,996
How do humans participate in the runtime?

191
00:10:18,996 --> 00:10:24,079
How do we observe decisions that may and
may not be deterministic?

192
00:10:24,079 --> 00:10:28,365
And how do we build systems that can
evolve as

193
00:10:28,365 --> 00:10:31,852
both our understanding and the underlying
technology change?

194
00:10:31,852 --> 00:10:36,936
Those are the questions that the rest of
this journal will explore.

195
00:10:36,936 --> 00:10:41,362
So in this episode, I've established what
I currently mean

196
00:10:41,362 --> 00:10:44,964
when I describe Articulate as an AI-native
system.

197
00:10:44,964 --> 00:10:50,215
It isn't simply an existing application
with an LLM attached to it.

198
00:10:50,215 --> 00:10:52,992
Intelligence participates in the runtime
itself.

199
00:10:52,992 --> 00:10:57,418
It helps the system understand intent,
build context, retrieve knowledge,

200
00:10:57,418 --> 00:11:01,432
reason about problems, coordinate work and
collaborate with humans.

201
00:11:01,432 --> 00:11:05,034
I've also distinguished AI-native
architecture from agentic architecture.

202
00:11:05,034 --> 00:11:09,460
Agents may become important building
blocks within Articulate, but adding

203
00:11:09,460 --> 00:11:11,825
agents is not the objective.

204
00:11:11,825 --> 00:11:16,251
They are one possible way of organising
intelligent behaviour where

205
00:11:16,251 --> 00:11:18,616
the problem genuinely requires it.

206
00:11:18,616 --> 00:11:23,043
And perhaps the clearest test is this: If
AI were

207
00:11:23,043 --> 00:11:27,469
removed from Articulate, the system would
not merely lose a

208
00:11:27,469 --> 00:11:28,891
feature.

209
00:11:28,891 --> 00:11:32,081
Its architecture would have to change
fundamentally.

210
00:11:32,081 --> 00:11:36,507
But recognising that Articulate is
AI-native doesn't tell me how

211
00:11:36,507 --> 00:11:38,047
to design it.

212
00:11:38,047 --> 00:11:41,237
It introduces a much larger architectural
question.

213
00:11:41,237 --> 00:11:45,663
How should I approach the design of a
system where

214
00:11:45,663 --> 00:11:50,089
intelligence, conversation, context,
knowledge and uncertainty are all part of

215
00:11:50,089 --> 00:11:51,512
the runtime?

216
00:11:51,512 --> 00:11:56,763
That is the question I will begin
exploring in the next episode.
